docs.abstract: Even if you manage to ditch your iPhone, Apple’s hooks are still there.
docs.snippet: Even if you manage to ditch your iPhone, Apple’s hooks are still there.
docs.lead_paragraph: When I temporarily switched from an iPhone to an Android phone last week, I was bracing for a world of hurt. I’ve owned only Apple phones ever since buying the first-generation iPhone in 2007. And, like many, I’ve bought other Apple products that pair nicely, including AirPods, an Apple Watch and an iPad.

headline.main: Switching From iPhone to Android Is Easy. It’s the Aftermath That Stings.
headline.print_headline: Switching From an iPhone Is Easy (Until It’s Not)

docs.abstract: Firms like Experian and TransUnion say it is time for “buy now, pay later” loans to appear on consumer credit reports. The lenders aren’t ready to sign on.
docs.snippet: Firms like Experian and TransUnion say it is time for “buy now, pay later” loans to appear on consumer credit reports. The lenders aren’t ready to sign on.
docs.lead_paragraph: Shoppers in recent years have embraced “buy now, pay later” loans as an easy, interest-free way to purchase everything from sweaters to concert tickets.

headline.main: ‘Pay Later’ Lenders Have an Issue With Credit Bureaus

byline.original: By Jordyn Holman and Ben Casselman

docs.abstract: Automattic, the company behind WordPress.com, bought Beeper in an effort to build a system that works across Android and Apple devices.
docs.snippet: Automattic, the company behind WordPress.com, bought Beeper in an effort to build a system that works across Android and Apple devices.
docs.lead_paragraph: Beeper, the app that brought iPhone messaging features to Android smartphones, has been acquired by Automattic, the company behind WordPress.com, to support the development of a single service for sending and receiving chats from WhatsApp, Signal, LinkedIn and others.

headline.main: Beeper Messaging App Is Acquired as a Bet on a Regulatory Shift
headline.print_headline: Betting on a Regulatory Shift, Automattic Scoops Up Beeper Messaging App

docs.abstract: Apple said it removed WhatsApp and Threads from its China app offerings Friday on Beijing’s orders, amid technological tensions between the U.S. and China.
docs.snippet: Apple said it removed WhatsApp and Threads from its China app offerings Friday on Beijing’s orders, amid technological tensions between the U.S. and China.
docs.lead_paragraph: Apple said it pulled the Meta-owned apps WhatsApp and Threads from its app store in China on Friday on government orders, potentially escalating the war over technology between the United States and China.

headline.main: Apple Says It Was Ordered to Pull WhatsApp From China App Store
headline.print_headline: Apple Pulls Apps, It Says, On Orders From Beijing

byline.original: By Tripp Mickle and Mike Isaac

docs.abstract: This fall, the company will begin allowing customers to replace broken parts with used iPhone components without its previous software limits.
docs.snippet: This fall, the company will begin allowing customers to replace broken parts with used iPhone components without its previous software limits.
docs.lead_paragraph: Apple said Thursday that it would relax limits on repairing newer iPhones with used parts like screens, batteries and cameras, a reversal from its previous practice of using software to encourage people to work with new and more expensive Apple-approved parts.

headline.main: Apple Lifts Some Restrictions on iPhone Repairs
headline.print_headline: Apple Relaxes iPhone Repair Rules After Oregon Outlaws Coercive Practice

byline.original: By Tripp Mickle and Brian X. Chen

docs.abstract: The agreement would give the tech company worldwide rights for a monthlong World Cup-style competition between top teams set to take place next year.
docs.snippet: The agreement would give the tech company worldwide rights for a monthlong World Cup-style competition between top teams set to take place next year.
docs.lead_paragraph: FIFA, soccer’s global governing body, is close to an agreement with Apple that would give the tech company worldwide television rights for a major new tournament, a monthlong, World Cup-style competition for top teams that will be played for the first time in the United States next summer.

headline.main: FIFA Said to Be Close to TV Deal With Apple for New Tournament
headline.print_headline: FIFA Said to Be Discussing A Tournament With Apple
